Time: O(n) — we loop through each string once
Space: O(n) — storing character counts

Approach 3 — Single array of 26 integers (most efficient)
Since we're only dealing with lowercase English letters (a to z), we can use an array of exactly 26 numbers — one slot per letter. We increment for letters in s and decrement for letters in t. If all values end at 0, it's an anagram.
pythonclass Solution:
    def isAnagram(self, s: str, t: str) -> bool:

        # Step 1: Lengths must match
        if len(s) != len(t):
            return False

        # Step 2: Create an array of 26 zeros (one per letter a-z)
        count = [0] * 26

        # Step 3: For each position, +1 for s, -1 for t
        for i in range(len(s)):
            count[ord(s[i]) - ord('a')] += 1  # s adds to count
            count[ord(t[i]) - ord('a')] -= 1  # t subtracts from count

        # Step 4: If all zeros, every letter balanced out
        return all(x == 0 for x in count)
The ord() trick explained:
ord('a') = 97, ord('b') = 98, ord('c') = 99...
So ord('c') - ord('a') = 99 - 97 = 2, meaning 'c' maps to index 2.
Every letter maps neatly to indices 0–25.
Time: O(n) — one loop through both strings simultaneously
Space: O(1) — always exactly 26 numbers, no matter how long the input

